'''Nathan Kenneth Patterson''' (born 16 October 2001) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]] for {{English football updater|Everton}} club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

==Club career==
===Rangers===
A [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] youth graduate who attended [[Holyrood Secondary School]] in southern [[Glasgow]] as a participant in the [[Scottish Football Association]]'s 'Performance Schools' development programme,<ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/rangers/malky-mackay-on-why-four-stone-wet-through-and-five-feet-high-rangers-kid-was-always-destined-to-be-a-star-3253370 Malky Mackay on why 'four stone wet through and five feet high' Rangers kid was always destined to be a star], Stephen Halliday, The Scotsman, 28 May 2021</ref><ref>[https://www.tes.com/magazine/archived/scotland-players-old-schools-send-good-luck-messages Scotland players' old schools send good luck messages], Henry Hepburn, [[TES (magazine)]], 11 June 2021</ref> Patterson signed a new contract on 21 December 2019, keeping him at the club until 2022.<ref>{{ cite web|url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/academy-news/nathan-patterson-signs-new-contract/|website=rangers.co.uk|date=21 December 2019| title=Nathan Patterson Signs New Contract}}</ref> He made his debut on 17 January 2020, in a [[Scottish Cup]] match against [[Stranraer F.C.|Stranraer]] at [[Ibrox Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rangers 2–0 Stranraer|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51058102|website=BBC Sport|last=Watt|first=Martin|date=17 January 2020}}</ref> He made his league debut against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] on 22 August 2020, coming on as a substitute in the 86th minute in a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite web|date=23 August 2020|title=Rangers 2–0 Kilmarnock: 'Sharper' Kemar Roofe delights Steven Gerrard|website=BBC Sport| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53788425 |accessdate=24 August 2020}}</ref>

Patterson made his European debut on 10 December 2020, starting in a 2–0 away win against Polish side [[Lech Poznań]].<ref>{{cite web|date=23 August 2020|title=Lech Poznan 0–2 Rangers|website=BBC Sport|first=Andy|last=Campbell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55231015|accessdate=10 December 2020}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 25 February 2021, in a [[UEFA Europa League]] match against [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]], scoring 16.6 seconds after coming on as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite news| title=Rangers 5–2 Royal Antwerp |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56138759 | publisher=BBC | work=BBC Sport| date=25 February 2021 | first=Martin | last=Watt}}</ref> Patterson played regularly for Rangers during the later part of their 2020–21 title-winning season, deputising for the injured [[James Tavernier]], until he was suspended for breaching [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]] rules.<ref name = suspended>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56843698 |title=Rangers: Five players have appeal dismissed after Covid breach |website=BBC Sport |date=22 April 2021 |accessdate=23 April 2021}}</ref>

===Everton===
On 4 January 2022, Patterson signed for [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on a five-and-a-half-year deal.<ref name = everton>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59871706|title=Nathan Patterson: Everton complete signing of Scotland right-back from Rangers|website=BBC|date=4 January 2022|accessdate=4 January 2022}}</ref><ref name = sky/> The transfer fee was officially undisclosed, though it was believed to have been in the region of £11 million including add-ons.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/everton-seal-deal-for-right-back-nathan-patterson-from-rangers-70gxmjcph | title=Everton seal deal for right back Nathan Patterson from Rangers }}</ref><ref name = everton/><ref name = sky>{{Cite web|title=Nathan Patterson: Everton sign right-back from Rangers in £16m deal|url=https://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/12691/12508957/nathan-patterson-everton-sign-right-back-from-rangers-in-16m-deal|date=2022-01-04|access-date=2022-01-05|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref group=note>''The Times'' [https://www.thetimes.com/sport/football/article/everton-seal-deal-for-right-back-nathan-patterson-from-rangers-70gxmjcph reported] ({{subscription required}}) that the fee was £11 million ''inclusive'' of add-ons.</ref> Having been signed by manager [[Rafael Benitez]] who was soon sacked, Patterson's Everton career got off to a slow start, initially playing for the [[Everton F.C. Reserves and Academy|under-23s]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nathan Patterson handed Everton Under-23s debut|date=2022-01-24|url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/everton/news/nathan-patterson-handed-everton-under-23s-debut_476228.html|access-date=2022-02-05|website=SportsMole}}</ref> rather than the first team.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pirie|first=Mark|date=2022-02-05|title=Nathan Patterson post Rangers waiting game continues as new Everton boss Frank Lampard turns to Celtic flop|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/nathan-patterson-post-rangers-waiting-26148884|access-date=2022-02-05|website=Daily Record}}</ref> This trend continued for the entirety of the 2021–22 Premier League season, with Patterson making no first team appearances in the Premier League despite the club's continued high hopes for the player.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nathan Patterson Premier League statistics |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/74585/Nathan-Patterson/stats |access-date=23 May 2022 |date=23 May 2022}}</ref> These limited opportunities for Patterson were, until April, due to the team wanting to give Patterson the time to adjust to the pace and freneticism of the Premier League before handing him a full debut. However, Patterson was unable to play after from 10 April onwards due to an ankle injury sustained in Everton's final training session before playing West Ham on 3 April. This ankle injury required surgery and ruled Patterson out for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyland |first1=Patrick |title=Nathan Patterson Ankle Injury Requires Surgery |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3500773/2022/04/05/nathan-patterson-could-miss-rest-of-evertons-season-after-small-operation-on-ankle-injury/ |access-date=23 June 2022 |date=6 April 2022}}</ref>

Patterson was named to start in all of Everton's four pre-season games before the commencement of the 2022–23 season. Throughout pre-season, he managed a total of two assists, both coming in the match against Blackpool ([[Vitaliy Mykolenko]]'s 6th minute goal and [[Dele Alli]]'s 64th minute goal).<ref>{{cite news |title=Blackpool vs Everton Result, Score and Updates |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-blackpool-live-stream-score-24574640 |access-date=29 July 2022 |date=24 July 2022}}</ref> Patterson's positive performances in pre-season earned him the plaudits of both his manager<ref>{{cite news |title=Patterson earns Frank Lampard's praise |url=https://www.scottishdailyexpress.co.uk/sport/football/nathan-patterson-earns-frank-lampard-27568345 |access-date=29 July 2022 |date=25 July 2022}}</ref> and former footballers alike.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former Everton midfielder Scott Gemmill lauds Patterson's performances |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-nathan-patterson-tremendous-position-24591985 |access-date=29 July 2022 |date=26 July 2022}}</ref>

After suffering a serious injury against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 15 April 2024,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68858086|title=Nathan Patterson: Everton and Scotland right-back ruled out for season|work=BBC Sport |date=19 April 2024}}</ref> Patterson made his long-awaited return nearly ten months later in a 4–0 defeat to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/13262409/man-utd-4-0-everton-marcus-rashford-and-joshua-zirkzee-on-target-as-ruben-amorim-gets-first-premier-league-win|title=Man Utd 4–0 Everton: Marcus Rashford and Joshua Zirkzee on target as Ruben Amorim gets first Premier League win|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>

==International career==
Patterson has represented [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] at various youth levels up to [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21s]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nathan Patterson Scottish FA player profile|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=235749&lid=9|website=scottishfa.co.uk|accessdate=31 August 2020}}</ref> He was added to the [[Scotland national football team|full national squad]] for the first time in May 2021, ahead of the delayed [[UEFA Euro 2020]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57171330 |title=Scotland include Gilmour, Patterson & Turnbull for Euro finals |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=19 May 2021 |access-date=19 May 2021}}</ref> Patterson made his full international debut in a pre-tournament friendly against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57297065 |title=Luxembourg 0–1 Scotland |first=Martin |last=Watt |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2021 |accessdate=6 June 2021}}</ref> came off the bench during the Euros against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] at [[Hampden Park]], and made his first start against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] in September of that year during [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/andy-robertson-reveals-calm-down-chat-with-nathan-patterson-as-rangers-kid-hailed-for-scotland-display-3371745%3famp|title=Andy Robertson reveals 'calm down' chat with Nathan Patterson as Rangers kid hailed for Scotland display|publisher=The Scotsman |date=6 September 2021|access-date=10 September 2021}}</ref> On 12 November 2021, Patterson scored a first international goal when he opened the scoring in a vital 2–0 win away in Moldova before setting up [[Ché Adams]] for the second. This victory saw Scotland qualify for a World Cup play-off place.<ref name="1st international goal"/>

Due to the injury he picked up while playing for Everton, Patterson missed out on [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishnews.com/sport/soccer/scotland-right-backs-nathan-patterson-and-aaron-hickey-ruled-out-of-euro-2024-YK4TFNRJK5NFDFBXFHVZTM7WCU/|title=Scotland right-backs Nathan Patterson and Aaron Hickey ruled out of Euro 2024|date=20 May 2024|website=The Irish News}}</ref>

==Personal life==
In February 2021, Patterson was one of five Rangers players who were issued with a Fixed Penalty Notice by [[Police Scotland]] "for attending an illegal gathering of 10 people in a flat" in breach of lockdown rules during the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lindsay |first1=Matthew |title=Rangers midfielder Bongani Zungu set to depart Ibrox this summer following Covid-19 lockdown breach |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/19106272.rangers-midfielder-bongani-zungu-set-depart-ibrox-summer-following-covid-19-lockdown-breach/ |access-date=23 February 2021 |work=Herald Scotland |date=20 February 2021}}</ref> Patterson and the other players were banned for six games by the [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] for the breach, although part of that sentence was suspended.<ref name = suspended/>

